To determine whether (A x B) x C is equivalent to A x (B x C), we will first find the Cartesian products of the sets.

(A x B) x C:
1. Find A x B: { (1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4) }
2. Now find (A x B) x C: { ((1,3),5), ((1,4),5), ((2,3),5), ((2,4),5) }

A x (B x C):
1. Find B x C: { (3,5), (4,5) }
2. Now find A x (B x C): { (1,(3,5)), (1,(4,5)), (2,(3,5)), (2,(4,5)) }

Comparing the two results, we can see that (A x B) x C is not equivalent to A x (B x C) as the elements in the sets are different:

(A x B) x C = { ((1,3),5), ((1,4),5), ((2,3),5), ((2,4),5) }
A x (B x C) = { (1,(3,5)), (1,(4,5)), (2,(3,5)), (2,(4,5)) }
